articles.headline: California Counts Methodically as House Control Hangs in the Balance
articles.snippet: Nine of the 16 races that will determine which party controls the House of Representatives are in California. No state takes longer to tally votes.
articles.abstract: Nine of the 16 races that will determine which party controls the House of Representatives are in California. No state takes longer to tally votes.
articles.lead_paragraph: The nation is again waiting on California to finish tallying votes almost a week after Election Day.
articles.byline: By Soumya Karlamangla, Orlando Mayorquín and Coral Murphy Marcos

articles.headline: Why Was There a Broad Drop-Off in Democratic Turnout in 2024?
articles.snippet: Many Democrats failed to turn out to vote at the rate they did in 2020 when they ousted Donald Trump, according to an analysis of election data.
articles.abstract: Many Democrats failed to turn out to vote at the rate they did in 2020 when they ousted Donald Trump, according to an analysis of election data.
articles.lead_paragraph: Voters in liberal strongholds across the country, from city centers to suburban stretches, failed to show up to vote for Vice President Kamala Harris at the levels they had for Joseph R. Biden Jr. four years earlier, contributing significantly to her defeat by Donald J. Trump, according to a New York Times analysis of preliminary election data.

articles.headline: Europe Braces for Trump: ‘Worst Economic Nightmare Has Come True’
articles.snippet: The United States is the biggest trading partner for the European Union and Britain, whose economies could be at risk from the president-elect’s policies.
articles.abstract: The United States is the biggest trading partner for the European Union and Britain, whose economies could be at risk from the president-elect’s policies.
articles.lead_paragraph: The outlook for Europe’s economy has been disappointing.

articles.headline: Trump’s Tariffs Could Deal a Blow to Mexico’s Car Factories
articles.snippet: The president-elect has said he could impose punitive tariffs on car imports from Mexico, a move that could hurt factories and workers on both sides of the border.
articles.abstract: The president-elect has said he could impose punitive tariffs on car imports from Mexico, a move that could hurt factories and workers on both sides of the border.
articles.lead_paragraph: Until a few years ago there was not much in this patch of desert 250 miles north of Mexico City but rattlesnakes, coyotes and cactus. Today, it is gleaming evidence of the country’s growing importance as an auto producer.

articles.headline: Chronic Brain Trauma Is Extensive in Navy’s Elite Speedboat Crews
articles.snippet: The pounding that sailors’ brains take from years of high-speed wave-slamming in the Special Boat Teams can cause symptoms that wreck their careers — and their lives.
articles.abstract: The pounding that sailors’ brains take from years of high-speed wave-slamming in the Special Boat Teams can cause symptoms that wreck their careers — and their lives.
articles.lead_paragraph: In the year before Troy Norrell died, he grew convinced that the government had somehow infiltrated his brain. And in a way, he was right.

articles.headline: Hong Kong’s Tycoons Are Selling Trophy Homes at Fire Sale Prices
articles.snippet: China’s economic downturn has not been kind to the ultrarich who made their wealth on its rise. In their haste to cough up cash, Hong Kong’s luxury property market has had some fire sales.
articles.abstract: China’s economic downturn has not been kind to the ultrarich who made their wealth on its rise. In their haste to cough up cash, Hong Kong’s luxury property market has had some fire sales.
articles.lead_paragraph: One by one, tycoons who built their wealth on China’s economic rise have been giving up their trophy homes in Hong Kong.
articles.byline: By Alexandra Stevenson and Anthony Kwan

articles.headline: Was the Trump Election a Setback for Women? Even Women Do Not Agree.
articles.snippet: Kamala Harris would have been the first female president in the nation’s nearly 250-year history. But many women chose Donald Trump, despite his history of sexism and his support for the end of Roe v. Wade.
articles.abstract: Kamala Harris would have been the first female president in the nation’s nearly 250-year history. But many women chose Donald Trump, despite his history of sexism and his support for the end of Roe v. Wade.
articles.lead_paragraph: To many left-leaning Americans, it is resoundingly clear that women who backed Donald J. Trump in the presidential election voted against their own self-interest.

articles.headline: Attack, Withdraw, Return: Israel’s Bloody Cycle of War in North Gaza
articles.snippet: Israel said its forces had returned to northern Gaza to fight a Hamas resurgence. That has brought a new round of suffering for residents.
articles.abstract: Israel said its forces had returned to northern Gaza to fight a Hamas resurgence. That has brought a new round of suffering for residents.
articles.lead_paragraph: When Israeli forces first swarmed into Gaza last year, they targeted North Gaza, an area stretching across densely packed urban centers and small strawberry farms near the border with Israel.
articles.byline: By Jack Nicas, Adam Rasgon and Hiba Yazbek

articles.headline: Archbishop of Canterbury Resigns Over U.K. Church Abuse Scandal
articles.snippet: The Most Rev. Justin Welby, the leader of 85 million Anglicans worldwide, announced his resignation days after a report found he had taken insufficient action over claims of abuse.
articles.abstract: The Most Rev. Justin Welby, the leader of 85 million Anglicans worldwide, announced his resignation days after a report found he had taken insufficient action over claims of abuse.
articles.lead_paragraph: The archbishop of Canterbury, the Most Rev. Justin Welby, resigned on Tuesday after a damning report concluded that he had failed to pursue a proper investigation into claims of widespread abuse of boys and young men decades ago at Christian summer camps.
articles.byline: By Stephen Castle and Mark Landler

articles.headline: Exxon Chief to Trump: Don’t Withdraw From Paris Climate Deal
articles.snippet: Darren Woods was one of only a few Western oil executives attending a global climate conference in Baku, Azerbaijan.
articles.abstract: Darren Woods was one of only a few Western oil executives attending a global climate conference in Baku, Azerbaijan.
articles.lead_paragraph: Darren Woods, the chief executive of Exxon Mobil, cautioned President-elect Donald J. Trump on Tuesday against withdrawing from the Paris agreement to curb climate-warming emissions, saying Mr. Trump risked leaving a void at the negotiating table.
